fastEmbedR third-party provenance notice

fastEmbedR is distributed under GPL (>= 3).

This notice documents code provenance and design references for the cleaned
package. The public API is focused on nearest-neighbour search and native UMAP
and openTSNE-style embeddings from precomputed KNN matrices. The earlier
legacy t-SNE, InfoTSNE, PaCMAP, TriMap, and LocalMAP reducers were removed from
the exported package API.

Optional FAISS backend
----------------------

The optional `nn(..., backend = "faiss")` and
`nn(..., backend = "faiss_ivf")` paths link to the FAISS C++ library when
FAISS is available at package build time:

  FAISS
  Repository: https://github.com/facebookresearch/faiss
  License: MIT

FAISS is not vendored into fastEmbedR. The package build system only links to
an external FAISS installation when requested or automatically detected.

Optional RAPIDS cuVS backend
----------------------------

The optional `nn(..., backend = "cuda_cuvs")`,
`nn(..., backend = "cuda_cuvs_bruteforce")`, and
`nn(..., backend = "cuda_cuvs_nndescent")` paths link to an external RAPIDS
cuVS installation only when it is available at package build time:

  RAPIDS cuVS
  Repository: https://github.com/rapidsai/cuvs
  License: Apache-2.0

No RAPIDS source files are vendored into fastEmbedR. cuVS is used only for
nearest-neighbour search. A GPU nearest-neighbour backend does not relabel the
native openTSNE optimizer as GPU work.

DLPack C ABI header
-------------------

The optional cuVS C API exchanges tensors through DLPack ABI structs. Some
RAPIDS wheel installations do not install a standalone `dlpack/dlpack.h`
header, so fastEmbedR vendors a minimal compatibility header containing only
the stable DLPack C enum and struct definitions used by the cuVS bridge:

  DLPack
  Repository: https://github.com/dmlc/dlpack
  License: Apache-2.0

The compatibility header is stored at `src/dlpack/dlpack.h`.

Native NN-descent design references
-----------------------------------

The experimental native NN-descent backends were informed by:

  mlx-vis
  Author: Han Xiao
  Repository: https://github.com/hanxiao/mlx-vis
  License: Apache-2.0

  annembed
  Author: Jean-Pierre Both
  Repository: https://github.com/jean-pierreBoth/annembed
  License: MIT OR Apache-2.0

The transferred ideas are algorithmic: NEW/OLD neighbour tracking, adaptive
candidate expansion, reverse-candidate pruning near convergence, and active-row
candidate generation. After inspecting `mlx_vis/_tsne/tsne.py`, the Metal
openTSNE FFT-grid roadmap also uses mlx-vis as an architectural reference for
GPU-resident interpolation-grid scatter/gather, FFT-style repulsive-force
evaluation, and fused optimizer updates. The implementation is native
R/C++/Metal/CUDA code for fastEmbedR. It does not vendor mlx-vis or annembed
source files, link to those projects, or call Python/MLX at runtime.

The native Metal UMAP backend uses mlx-vis as a design reference for keeping
the graph/optimizer pipeline GPU-resident. Its KNN-input path computes smooth
KNN bandwidths, fuzzy graph weights, epoch schedules, graph-smoothed
initialization, and UMAP SGD in C++/Metal kernels. It does not call Python/MLX
or reuse CPU UMAP graph builders for Metal-labelled UMAP runs.

openTSNE design reference
-------------------------

The native openTSNE-style full t-SNE optimizer and the fixed-reference
transform used by `transform_tsne()` and `landmark_tsne()` were informed by:

  openTSNE
  Repository: https://github.com/pavlin-policar/openTSNE
  License: BSD-3-Clause

For `opentsne_knn()`, `embed_knn(method = "opentsne")`, and `opentsne()`,
fastEmbedR implements a native C++ two-phase optimizer matching openTSNE's
high-level contract: early exaggeration followed by normal optimization,
automatic learning rate `n / exaggeration`, momentum/gain updates,
max-step clipping, sparse positive KNN forces, and native `"fft"` or `"exact"`
negative-gradient choices. The older Barnes-Hut route was removed after the
MNIST 70k benchmarks showed the FFT-grid path was the useful CPU standard.

On macOS with Metal, `opentsne_knn(..., backend = "metal")` has a native
Objective-C++/Metal exact path for moderate datasets. It computes row
perplexity probabilities, dense symmetric KNN affinities, global t-SNE
normalization, gains/momentum updates, and the final layout in Metal kernels.
The exact Metal path is O(n^2) in memory and time. Large-data Metal openTSNE
uses a native FFT/FIt-SNE-style negative-gradient path: the interpolation-grid
scatter, padded-grid FFT convolution, grid gather, sparse attractive forces,
and gain/momentum update run in Objective-C++/Metal kernels. CUDA uses package
CUDA kernels plus cuFFT for the corresponding FFT-grid path. The earlier
sampled full-embedding GPU repulsion path is not exposed as openTSNE because it
changes the optimization mathematics.

The implementation is fastEmbedR C++ code and does not vendor, link to, or
call openTSNE's Python or Cython implementation. CPU
`negative_gradient_method = "fft"` is a native grid approximation inspired
by FIt-SNE/openTSNE/t-SNE-CUDA. CPU uses C++ grid FFTs. Metal uses package-native
Objective-C++/Metal grid scatter, FFT convolution, gather, and optimizer
kernels. CUDA uses package-native grid scatter/gather, sparse attractive
forces, gain/momentum kernels, and cuFFT convolution.

t-SNE-CUDA design reference
---------------------------

The native fixed-reference transform design and CPU grid-FFT negative-gradient
path use architectural ideas described in:

  Chan DM, Rao R, Huang F, Canny J. t-SNE-CUDA: GPU-Accelerated t-SNE and its
  Applications to Modern Data. arXiv:1807.11824v1, 2018.

  CannyLab/tsne-cuda
  Repository: https://github.com/CannyLab/tsne-cuda
  License: BSD-3-Clause

The transferred ideas are architectural: keep reference coordinates, query
coordinates, gains, updates, and repulsive-force state resident on the
accelerator during fixed-reference projection; and split t-SNE optimization
into sparse attractive forces plus interpolated/grid negative forces.
fastEmbedR does not vendor, copy, link to, or call t-SNE-CUDA source code.
